{{Criminology and penology}}
In [[criminology]], '''racial invariance''' refers to a hypothesis that the effects of structural disadvantage on rates of violent crime are the same for all [[Race (human categorization)|racial]] groups.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Laurence |first=James |title=Community Disadvantage and Race-Specific Rates of Violent Crime: An Investigation into the "Racial Invariance" Hypothesis in the United Kingdom |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01639625.2014.982749 |journal=Deviant Behavior |volume=36 |issue=12 |pages=974–995 |doi=10.1080/01639625.2014.982749}}</ref> This hypothesis is a major component of structural perspectives on the [[causes of crime]], such as [[social disorganization theory]] and [[anomie]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hannon |first=Lance |last2=DeFina |first2=Robert |title=Violent Crime in African American and White Neighborhoods: Is Poverty's Detrimental Effect Race-Specific? |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1300/J134v09n03_03 |journal=Journal of Poverty |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=49–67 |doi=10.1300/j134v09n03_03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Ousey |first=Graham C. |date=1999-05-01 |title=Homicide, Structural Factors, and the Racial Invariance Assumption* |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1745-9125.1999.tb00491.x/abstract |journal=Criminology |language=en |volume=37 |issue=2 |pages=405–426 |doi=10.1111/j.1745-9125.1999.tb00491.x |issn=1745-9125}}</ref> It can be traced back to [[William Julius Wilson]]'s 1987 book ''[[The Truly Disadvantaged]]'', which argued that racial differences in crime rates are due to differences in the communities in which American whites and blacks live.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Steffensmeier |first=Darrell |last2=Ulmer |first2=Jeffery T. |last3=Feldmeyer |first3=Ben |last4=Harris |first4=Casey T. |date=2010-11-01 |title=Scope and Conceptual Issues in Testing the Race–Crime Invariance Thesis: Black, White, and Hispanic Comparisons* |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1745-9125.2010.00214.x/abstract |journal=Criminology |language=en |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=1133–1169 |doi=10.1111/j.1745-9125.2010.00214.x |issn=1745-9125|pmc=4233132 }}</ref> Since then, it has become a major component of the [[general theory of crime]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Unnever |first=James D. |last2=Barnes |first2=J. C. |last3=Cullen |first3=Francis T. |title=The Racial Invariance Thesis Revisited |url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1043986215607254 |journal=Journal of Contemporary Criminal Justice |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=7–26 |doi=10.1177/1043986215607254}}</ref>

